Recommendations
We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed, to implement the following internal control measures:
Avail of the payroll facility offered by the LBP for the disbursement of salaries, wages, honoraria, and SC-SocPen payouts to minimize the need for CAs;
Ensure that the fidelity bond of each SDO is sufficient to cover their accountability for time-bound operating expenditures;
Prohibit the grant of additional CAs to AOs with unliquidated balances, to prevent exceeding the allowable bond limit; and
Require the immediate liquidation of all outstanding CAs of SDOs in accordance with existing regulations.

Recommendations
We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:
The General Service Officer (GSO) to prepare and submit the IIRUP, based on the RPCPPE, using the prescribed format for all PPE found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed;
The GSO, through its disposal committee, to conduct immediate disposal of all unserviceable properties following the procedures set forth in COA Circular 92-386, to prevent further deterioration and loss of additional income;
The Municipal Accountant to derecognize/drop from the books of accounts all unserviceable properties after disposal based on the properly accomplished IIRUP, Official Receipts and other pertinent documents and recognize gain/loss on disposal, if any.

Recommendations
We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:
Their implementing offices to ensure that all procurement be undertaken through the BAC as required by RA 9184 and its RIRR;
The BAC to:
If warranted, prepare BAC Resolution recommending to the Mayor as the head of procuring entity the termination of the contract in accordance with Annex “I” of the RIRR of RA 9184 on the basis of breach contract;
Strictly follow the procedures and documentary requirements for all procurement methods adopted in accordance with RA 9184 and its RIRR, especially the posting of performance security in order for the Municipality to be protected in case of breach of contract;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to derecognize the accounts payable after the contract is terminated.

We recommended that Management:
direct the Inventory Committee to conduct on a full-time basis and within a specific period of time, a complete annual physical count, including assignment of property number stickers to all property, plant and equipment of the Municipality to prove their existence, determine the condition and the valuation, and prepare the RPCPPE;
designate personnel each from the accounting and property offices who shall maintain and update the PPE Ledger/Property Cards and regularly reconcile their records, as well as maintain updated ARE and safekeeping of all pertinent documents relative to the acquisition of properties;
require the Municipal Accountant to compute the depreciation of all depreciable PPE and ensure that the computed depreciation are properly recorded in the books to reflect in the financial statements the correct value thereof; and
instruct all the departments to fill out completely and correctly the ARE with necessary details such as brand name, color, model, applicable serial number, and other important information of the property.

We recommended that Management:
strictly adhere to the rules and regulations on inter-agency fund transfers, comply with the abovementioned required documents and submit to COA the following:
Joint Undertakings;
Program of Works;
Official Receipts;
Certification of Accountant;
Actions taken on the deficient contract/joint undertaking; and
Authority of the Acting Municipal Mayor to enter into contract
prepare the following adjusting entry to establish accountability on the grant, utilization and liquidation of the fund transfers to barangays and submit copy of the journal entry voucher:
Due From Other LGUs (5-02-14-030)	            ₱41,800,000.00
Prior Period Adjustment (3-01-01-020)	            ₱41,800,000.00

We recommended that Management:
direct all accountable officials and employees to use the LGU’s Motor Vehicle strictly for official business with approved trip tickets and related supporting documents and to park them on the designated government parking space after office hours/completion of authorized travel and during non-working holidays;
direct all department heads to properly monitor their records on the use of government vehicles assigned to them and submit their reports together with approved trip tickets to assigned responsible personnel/GSO who will summarize and submit the same to accounting for the payment of billed gas consumption;
direct the GSO to mark all the LGU’s motor vehicles with “FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY” in accordance to COA Circular No. 75-6; and
strictly adhere to the cited COA rules and regulations on use of government vehicle.

We recommended that Management:
facilitate the preparation and approval of a supplemental budget for this fund to properly utilize and implement it in accordance with the cited LBC;
direct project proponents to prospectively develop a well-planned program/budget proposal of programs/activities to promote better quality of project implementation and reports/documentations submitted to COA and stakeholders;
provide for the resources in accordance with existing rules and regulations to facilitate the submission of liquidation reports for the food assistance program amounting to ₱975,000.00 of MSWDO; and
strictly adhere to the guidelines/rules, regulations and specific purpose of funds received set forth in LBC No. 134 regarding LGSF-DRRAP.

We recommended that Management:
strictly adhere to Section 2.6 of DBM LBC No. 124 and government procurement law on the use of fund for COVID-19-related expenses;
direct the MPDO/MBO to explain for the non-compliance to Section 2.6 of DBM LBC No. 124 and BAC for the use of direct contracting on the purchase of disinfectant and sanitizers;
direct the concerned responsible management personnel of MO, RHU and MSWDO to immediately submit the liquidation reports of the transactions enumerated in the 2nd table for proper review, accounting and recording; and
install strong internal controls on inventory taking and reporting in accordance with the inventory process under Section 122 of MNGAS and submit timely liquidation reports to avoid misuse/loss/unaccounted goods.

We recommended that Management:
direct the Municipal Budget Office to submit to COA the registries of appropriation and allotments for CY 2021 with required data and information for verification/validation;
direct the Municipal Budget Office to establish and maintain its Registries not only on a per Office basis, but also per Expense Class, accessible for budgetary comments/recommendations for possible need of realignment/augmentation within the year and available for auditorial visit any time;
stop the improper/invalid realignments/augmentation from unspent current operating expenses and adhere strictly to Section 321 and/or 336 of LGC on use of savings;
strictly follow the provisions of Section 314, LGC during the executive preparation and legislative review and approval of Annual Budget;
present in prospective Supplemental Budget/s a breakdown and total Source of Fund and Use of Fund not only per Office basis, but also per Expense Class; and
account for the variance of ₱3.51 million between the Slashed and Additional amounts in the approved annual budget for CY 2021.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the supporting schedule of Due to BIR account in order to identify the specific employees/personnel/supplier with unremitted withheld taxes and to establish the accuracy of the balance of this inter-agency payables account;
facilitate the immediate remittance of all valid tax liabilities to Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR);

take necessary and appropriate action on the identification and preparation of supporting schedule of JOs and/or Contractual employees without TIN but whose income were subjected to withholding taxes in 2015; and

strictly observe the prescribed guidelines and timelines in the remittance of withheld taxes to avoid fines and penalties.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Assessor to consistently submit to MTO an updated Assessment Roll to establish an accurate RPT and SET receivables;
require the Municipal Treasurer to update the RPT Account Register of Individual Taxpayers to reflect the correct amount of RPT and SET Receivables basing on the updated Assessment Roll from the Municipal Assessor and submit them to the Municipal Accountant as reference for setting up of the RPT and SET receivables at the beginning of the year;

through the Municipal Accountant, reconcile records with the Municipal Treasurer, and thereafter effect the adjusting entries to provide correct balances in the ensuing Financial Statements; and

intensify revenue collection efforts by strictly enforcing existing tax laws and adopt the most efficient, effective and economical measures to improve the LGU’s collection system and revenue generation.

